../stage_02/agent.log:1273:../../../../../runs/error-prone-examples/elasticsearch-password-ingress-audit-change-plan-20260616_095347/stages/stage_05/agent.log:118:{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01JQUWsRVQVki727vKwXmDk8","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a comprehensive view of the cluster. Let me compile the migration plan:\n\n**Current State Summary:**\n\n1. **Cluster**: `elasticsearch`, 3-node StatefulSet (`es-0`, `es-1`, `es-2`), all running version 8.11.1\n2. **Version**: 8.11.1, Lucene 9.8.0, JDK 21.0.1, build_type: docker\n   - Minimum wire compat: 7.17.0\n   - Minimum index compat: 7.0.0\n3. **Node Roles**: All nodes are configured with every role (data, master, ingest, ml, transform, and all data tier variants), meaning there's no role separation across the cluster\n4. **Resources**: Each node has 512MB heap allocation and 1Gi memory limit with 1Gi storage per PVC\n5. **Security**: Currently disabled across the board—no authentication, no SSL/TLS for HTTP or transport—though there's a critical mismatch between the ConfigMap annotation and the actual running configuration\n\n. The original intended setup had security enabled with TLS certificates, but someone manually reconfigured the cluster to disable it. The cluster still has the necessary secrets (`es-http-tls` with certificates and `elastic-password` credentials) sitting unused\n6. **Ingress**: Traffic comes through `es.example.com` with TLS termination at the nginx ingress layer, but the backend connection to `es-http:9200` is completely unencrypted since security is disabled—creating a gap between encrypted external traffic and plaintext internal communication. There's also an `elastic-password-next` secret suggesting a planned password rotation that never happened\n7. **Index**: A single `test-index` with one primary shard exists in the cluster\n8. **Cluster Settings**: No custom configurations beyond defaults\n9. **ILM**: Only the built-in managed policies are present, none are actively in use\n10. **Index Templates**: All templates are system-provided (kibana-reporting, monitoring, fleet, etc.)\n11. **Snapshots**: No backup repositories are configured\n12. **OS Memory**: Each pod has 1GB total memory and is running at 94-95% capacity—extremely tight\n13. **Disk**: About 1TB of shared host disk space is available per node\n\nThe main problems I need to address are the security mismatch where credentials and TLS infrastructure exist but are completely disabled, the severe memory pressure on the pods, and the lack of any backup strategy. I also need to remove the initial master nodes setting since it's only required during bootstrap and can cause restart issues. The ingress is currently passing unencrypted traffic to the Elasticsearch nodes, so I'll need to enable HTTP SSL on the backend before upgrading. There's no custom ILM policy in place either, which I should set up for the test index. The JVM version is fine—21 is LTS and compatible with 8.12+.\n\nNow I'm putting together a comprehensive migration plan that covers pre-upgrade validation, security hardening with TLS configuration, and password rotation procedures.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1857,"cache_read_input_tokens":41801,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1857},"output_tokens":29,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b5a71215-f054-45aa-8821-4b71df5c2c8d","uuid":"bbc30ee7-b079-4b56-9e83-e536fa6cefa4","request_id":"req_011Cc6pRbpNyNRARkwAnhTb6"}
../stage_02/agent.log:1274:../../../../../runs/error-prone-examples/elasticsearch-password-ingress-audit-change-plan-20260616_095347/stages/stage_05/agent.log:120:{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01JQUWsRVQVki727vKwXmDk8","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01FUeYiub2annZTLY5kZ5UQk","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"cat <<'PLAN_EOF' > /tmp/plan.md\n# Elasticsearch Cluster — Change & Migration Plan\n**Prepared:** 2026-06-16  \n**Cluster:** elasticsearch (namespace: elasticsearch)  \n**Reviewed-by:** (SRE Lead — pending approval)  \n**Status:** DRAFT — do not apply until approved\n\n---\n\n## 1. Current State Inventory\n\n### 1.1 Topology\n\n| Resource | Detail |\n|---|---|\n| StatefulSet | `es` — 3 replicas |\n| Pods | es-0, es-1, es-2 (all Running) |\n| Services | es-http (ClusterIP :9200), es-nodes (Headless :9300) |\n| Ingress | elasticsearch → es.example.com (nginx, TLS 443) |\n| Image | docker.elastic.co/elasticsearch/elasticsearch:**8.11.1** |\n| Lucene | 9.8.0 |\n| JDK | OpenJDK 21.0.1 (bundled) |\n| Min wire compat | 7.17.0 |\n| Min index compat | 7.0.0 |\n\n### 1.2 Node Roles (all three nodes identical)\n\nAll nodes carry every role:\n`data, data_cold, data_content, data_frozen, data_hot, data_warm, ingest, master, ml, remote_cluster_client, transform`\n\nNo role separation — all nodes are both master-eligible and data nodes.\n\n### 1.3 Resource Allocation (per node)\n\n| Setting | Value |\n|---|---|\n| JVM heap | -Xms512m / -Xmx512m (512 MiB) |\n| Container memory limit | 1 Gi |\n| Container CPU limit | none |\n| PVC storage | 1 Gi |\n| Observed heap usage | 30–58% |\n| Observed OS mem usage | 94–95% |\n\n### 1.4 Security Configuration (CURRENT — DEGRADED)\n\nThe `es-config` ConfigMap currently running:\n\n```yaml\nxpack.security.enabled: false\nxpack.security.http.ssl.enabled: false\nxpack.security.transport.ssl.enabled: false\n```\n\n**The original intended configuration** (visible in the ConfigMap's last-applied annotation) had security fully enabled:\n- xpack.security.enabled: true\n- HTTP TLS using Secret `es-http-tls` (tls.crt / tls.key / ca.crt)\n- Transport TLS with certificate verification mode\n\n**This means security was disabled at some point after initial deployment.** The TLS Secret (`es-http-tls`) still exists and is structurally intact. Two password secrets exist:\n- `elastic-password` — current credential\n- `elastic-password-next` — a new credential prepared for rotation (not yet activated)\n\nThe Ingress enforces HTTPS (force-ssl-redirect: true, TLS via `es-ingress-tls`) but the upstream connection from nginx to es-http:9200 is **plaintext** because HTTP SSL is off. This is a security gap: ingress TLS terminates at the load-balancer but data flows unencrypted inside the cluster.\n\n### 1.5 Cluster Settings\n\nPersistent and transient cluster settings: **none** (all defaults).\n\nNotable active defaults:\n- `action.destructive_requires_name: true` ✓ (safe default, keep)\n- `action.auto_create_index: true` (permissive — review per workload)\n- `cluster.auto_shrink_voting_configuration: true` ✓\n\n`cluster.initial_master_nodes` is still present in elasticsearch.yml. This setting is only needed for initial cluster bootstrap and should be removed for all upgrade/restart cycles.\n\n### 1.6 Indices\n\n| Index | Shards | Replicas | Tier Preference | Docs |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| test-index | 1 | 1 | data_content | 1 |\n\nShard allocation routing: `_tier_preference: data_content` (set on the index).\n\nNo custom index templates. No user-defined ILM policies. All ILM policies present are Elastic built-in managed policies (90-days-default, ilm-history-ilm-policy, .monitoring-8-ilm-policy, etc.) and none are currently attached to `test-index`.\n\n### 1.7 Snapshots\n\nNo snapshot repository is configured. There is no automated backup mechanism in place.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Risk Register\n\n| ID | Risk | Severity | Mitigation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| R1 | Security disabled — plaintext HTTP inside cluster | **Critical** | Re-enable xpack.security before any upgrade |\n| R2 | No snapshot repository — no rollback point | **Critical** | Configure repository and take snapshot before upgrade |\n| R3 | `elastic-password-next` exists but is inactive — password rotation incomplete | High | Complete or abort the rotation before proceeding |\n| R4 | `cluster.initial_master_nodes` still set — can prevent clean restart | High | Remove from elasticsearch.yml pre-upgrade |\n| R5 | OS memory at 94–95% — OOM risk during rolling restart | High | Increase container memory limit to ≥2 Gi before upgrade |\n| R6 | All nodes carry all roles — no quorum isolation | Medium | Consider dedicated master nodes at next topology change |\n| R7 | No ILM policy on test-index — unbounded growth | Low | Attach an appropriate ILM policy |\n| R8 | action.auto_create_index=true — unexpected index creation | Low | Restrict to explicit patterns if data model is stable |\n\n---\n\n## 3. Pre-Upgrade Steps (must complete before any version bump)\n\nThese changes are prerequisite and MUST be reviewed, approved, and applied in sequence. None of them touch the Elasticsearch version.\n\n### Step 1 — Resolve the Password Rotation\n\nA `elastic-password-next` Secret exists but security is currently disabled, so it has no effect. Before re-enabling security, decide:\n\n- **Option A (abort rotation):** Delete `elastic-password-next`. Keep `elastic-password` as the active credential.\n- **Option B (complete rotation):** Re-enable security (Step 2), verify `elastic-password-next` grants full access, then delete `elastic-password` and update all consumers.\n\nRecommendation: Option A unless the rotation was intentional and documented. Either way, do not proceed with two password secrets in an undefined state.\n\n### Step 2 — Re-Enable xpack.security\n\nUpdate the `es-config` ConfigMap to restore the security block that was present in the original intended configuration:\n\n```yaml\n# Changes to es-config elasticsearch.yml:\nxpack.security.enabled: true\nxpack.security.http.ssl.enabled: true\nxpack.security.http.ssl.certificate: /usr/share/elasticsearch/config/certs/tls.crt\nxpack.security.http.ssl.key: /usr/share/elasticsearch/config/certs/tls.key\nxpack.security.http.ssl.certificate_authorities: /usr/share/elasticsearch/config/certs/ca.crt\nxpack.security.transport.ssl.enabled: true\nxpack.security.transport.ssl.certificate: /usr/share/elasticsearch/config/certs/tls.crt\nxpack.security.transport.ssl.key: /usr/share/elasticsearch/config/certs/tls.key\nxpack.security.transport.ssl.certificate_authorities: /usr/share/elasticsearch/config/certs/ca.crt\nxpack.security.transport.ssl.verification_mode: certificate\n```\n\nThe `es-http-tls` Secret already contains `tls.crt`, `tls.key`, and `ca.crt`. The volume mount for the `certs` volume already exists in the StatefulSet spec. This is a config-only change that requires a rolling restart.\n\n**Cert expiry must be verified before the restart.** Check:\n```bash\nkubectl -n elasticsearch get secret es-http-tls -o jsonpath='{.data.tls\\.crt}' \\\n  | base64 -d | openssl x509 -noout -dates\n```\nIf expired, rotate the TLS secret first (using openssl or cert-manager).\n\n**After the rolling restart**, update the Ingress backend annotation to route to HTTPS:\n```yaml\nnginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/backend-protocol: \"HTTPS\"\n```\n\n### Step 3 — Remove cluster.initial_master_nodes\n\nRemove `cluster.initial_master_nodes` from `es-config` elasticsearch.yml. This setting is only valid during initial cluster formation; leaving it set causes the cluster to attempt re-bootstrap on full restart and can prevent nodes from rejoining.\n\n```yaml\n# Remove this line from elasticsearch.yml:\n# cluster.initial_master_nodes: es-0,es-1,es-2\n```\n\nThis change requires a rolling restart (can be combined with Step 2 restart).\n\n### Step 4 — Increase Container Memory Limits\n\nOS memory utilization is 94–95% on all nodes. A rolling restart of 3 pods under this pressure risks OOM kills. Increase the container memory limit to at least 2 Gi before proceeding:\n\n```yaml\n# StatefulSet es — container elasticsearch:\nresources:\n  limits:\n    memory: 2Gi       # was 1Gi\n  requests:\n    memory: 2Gi       # add explicit request to match limit\n```\n\nThe JVM heap stays at 512 MiB (correct at ~25% of 2 Gi for mixed-role nodes). Do not increase heap without profiling — the overhead memory (off-heap caches, networking, ML) needs the headroom.\n\n### Step 5 — Configure a Snapshot Repository\n\nNo backup exists. Before any upgrade, a snapshot repository MUST be configured and a full snapshot taken.\n\n```bash\n# Example — S3-compatible repository (replace with actual bucket/region):\nPUT /_snapshot/backup-repo\n{\n  \"type\": \"s3\",\n  \"settings\": {\n    \"bucket\": \"<bucket-name>\",\n    \"region\": \"<aws-region>\"\n  }\n}\n\n# Take a full snapshot:\nPUT /_snapshot/backup-repo/pre-upgrade-8.11.1\n{\n  \"indices\": \"*\",\n  \"include_global_state\": true\n}\n```\n\nFor on-premise environments without S3, use a shared NFS path with the `fs` repository type and mount it into all pods via a PVC.\n\n**The upgrade must not start until the snapshot completes successfully (`state: SUCCESS`).**\n\n---\n\n## 4. Upgrade Procedure — 8.11.1 → 8.12.x (or 8.13.x)\n\nFollow the Elastic rolling upgrade path. Upgrading more than one minor version at a time is not supported.\n\n### 4.1 Choose Target Version\n\n- **8.12.x** is the immediate next minor. It introduced ESQL GA, connector service changes, and several security defaults changes.\n- **8.13.x** is the next step if jumping two minors (requires 8.11 → 8.12 → 8.13).\n- **9.x** requires completing the 8.x family first (upgrade to latest 8.x, resolve all deprecation warnings, then bump major).\n\nRecommendation: upgrade to the latest 8.12.x patch first, validate, then continue to 8.13.x in a separate change window.\n\n### 4.2 Pre-Upgrade Cluster Checks\n\n```bash\n# Verify cluster is green, no relocating/initializing shards:\nGET /_cluster/health\n\n# Check deprecation API for warnings that will become errors in the next version:\nGET /_migration/deprecations\n\n# Disable shard allocation (prevent unnecessary shard movement during restart):\nPUT /_cluster/settings\n{\n  \"persistent\": {\n    \"cluster.routing.allocation.enable\": \"primaries\"\n  }\n}\n\n# Flush all active write indices to reduce recovery time:\nPOST /_flush\n```\n\n### 4.3 Rolling Node Upgrade\n\nFor each pod (es-2, es-1, es-0 — restart non-master nodes first):\n\n1. Delete the pod (StatefulSet will recreate it with the new image):\n   ```bash\n   kubectl -n elasticsearch delete pod es-2\n   ```\n2. Wait for the new pod to be Ready and rejoin the cluster:\n   ```bash\n   kubectl -n elasticsearch rollout status statefulset/es\n   GET /_cat/nodes?v\n   ```\n3. Verify cluster health is green before proceeding to the next pod.\n\nTo trigger the image update, patch the StatefulSet image:\n```bash\nkubectl -n elasticsearch set image statefulset/es \\\n  elasticsearch=docker.elastic.co/elasticsearch/elasticsearch:8.12.2\n```\nThen delete pods one at a time as above.\n\n### 4.4 Re-Enable Shard Allocation\n\nAfter all nodes are running the new version and cluster is green:\n```bash\nPUT /_cluster/settings\n{\n  \"persistent\": {\n    \"cluster.routing.allocation.enable\": null\n  }\n}\n```\n\n### 4.5 Post-Upgrade Validation\n\n```bash\n# Version check:\nGET /\n\n# Cluster health green, correct node count:\nGET /_cluster/health\n\n# All shards assigned, no unassigned:\nGET /_cat/shards?v&h=index,shard,prirep,state,node\n\n# Verify test-index settings preserved:\nGET /test-index/_settings\n\n# Run deprecation check for next planned upgrade:\nGET /_migration/deprecations\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. Post-Upgrade Hardening Tasks\n\nThese are not blockers for the version bump but should be scheduled in the same change window or immediately after.\n\n### 5.1 ILM Policy for test-index\n\n`test-index` has no lifecycle policy. If it will receive ongoing writes, attach the built-in `90-days-default` policy or define a custom one:\n\n```bash\nPUT /test-index/_settings\n{\n  \"index.lifecycle.name\": \"90-days-default\"\n}\n```\n\n### 5.2 Node Role Separation (Next Topology Change)\n\nAll three nodes currently carry all roles. For production stability with more than a handful of indices, consider dedicating one or more nodes as master-eligible only (no data role). This prevents data-heavy workloads from starving master elections. This is a topology change that requires additional nodes and is deferred to the next scale-out window.\n\n### 5.3 CPU Limits\n\nNo CPU limits are set on the elasticsearch container. Add resource requests/limits to ensure Quality-of-Service classification (Guaranteed QoS):\n```yaml\nresources:\n  limits:\n    memory: 2Gi\n    cpu: \"2\"\n  requests:\n    memory: 2Gi\n    cpu: \"2\"\n```\n\n### 5.4 action.auto_create_index\n\nIf the index schema is controlled and unexpected indices are a concern, restrict auto-creation:\n```bash\nPUT /_cluster/settings\n{\n  \"persistent\": {\n    \"action.auto_create_index\": \".kibana*,.logstash*,.monitoring*,.watches*,.triggered_watches*,.security*,test-*\"\n  }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Rollback Plan\n\nIf the upgrade cannot complete or leaves the cluster in an unhealthy state:\n\n1. Re-enable the old image tag in the StatefulSet (`8.11.1`).\n2. Delete the affected pod(s) to force recreation from the old image.\n3. If data corruption occurred, restore from the pre-upgrade snapshot:\n   ```bash\n   POST /_snapshot/backup-repo/pre-upgrade-8.11.1/_restore\n   {\n     \"indices\": \"*\",\n     \"include_global_state\": true\n   }\n   ```\n\nNote: Elasticsearch indices written by 8.12+ **cannot be read by 8.11.x**. Rolling back after any write to a new-version index requires the snapshot restore path.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Change Window Estimate\n\n| Phase | Estimated Duration | Owner |\n|---|---|---|\n| Pre-checks and snapshot | 30–60 min | SRE |\n| Security re-enable + rolling restart | 20–40 min | SRE |\n| Image update (rolling, 3 nodes) | 15–30 min | SRE |\n| Post-upgrade validation | 15 min | SRE + Dev |\n| **Total** | **80–145 min** | |\n\nRecommend scheduling in a low-traffic window with a 3-hour maintenance slot to allow for unexpected delays.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Approval Checklist\n\n- [ ] SRE Lead reviewed and approved this plan\n- [ ] Snapshot repository configured and pre-upgrade snapshot verified SUCCESS\n- [ ] TLS certificate expiry verified (>30 days remaining)\n- [ ] Password rotation status resolved (elastic-password-next handled)\n- [ ] Change window scheduled and stakeholders notified\n- [ ] Rollback procedure confirmed tested in staging\nPLAN_EOF\nwc -c /tmp/plan.md","description":"Write migration plan to temp file and check size"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1857,"cache_read_input_tokens":41801,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1857},"output_tokens":29,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b5a71215-f054-45aa-8821-4b71df5c2c8d","uuid":"14b0d2a8-8fbf-44f4-929b-a65932772fb6","request_id":"req_011Cc6pRbpNyNRARkwAnhTb6"}
