../stage_02/agent.log:1309:../../../../../runs/error-prone-examples/elasticsearch-scale-users-audit-20260616_101353/stages/stage_04/agent.log:166:{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_013wr3zMARrBjR2hp9nBSAZq","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have enough information to write a comprehensive audit. Let me synthesize everything:\n\n## Summary of findings:\n\n### 1. TLS/Encryption\n- **HTTPS is enabled** on port 9200 (HTTP transport uses `security4`/TLS)\n- **Transport TLS is enabled** between nodes\n- TLS certificates are stored in `es-http-tls` secret\n  - CA cert: `CN=es-ca`, self-signed, expires 2027-06-16 (~1 year)\n  - Server cert: `CN=es-http`, issued by `CN=es-ca`, expires 2027-06-16\n- **Plain HTTP is rejected** - the HTTP port returns empty reply (TLS handshake required)\n- **FINDING**: Certificates are self-signed rather than issued by a trusted CA, which means encryption is in place but identity verification relies on internal trust only\n- **FINDING**: The `curl-test` pod bypasses certificate validation with `-sk` flags, creating a potential MITM vulnerability\n- **FINDING**: No explicit TLS version minimums or cipher suite restrictions are configured in the node settings\n\n### 2. Authentication\n\nSecurity is enabled across all nodes with two authentication realms configured: a file-based realm and a native realm. The `elastic` superuser password is set to `elasticpass` in a Kubernetes Secret—a weak, easily guessable credential that should be replaced with a strong random value. The deprecated `kibana` user is still active despite being marked for removal; the recommendation is to migrate to `kibana_system` instead. The file realm contains an additional superuser account `ops-user` alongside a read-only `report-user`.\n\nThe cluster lacks any Kubernetes NetworkPolicy resources, meaning any pod in the cluster can reach Elasticsearch on ports 9200 and 9300. Combined with the `network.host = 0.0.0.0` setting, this creates a significant exposure—the cluster relies entirely on Kubernetes network segmentation with no additional firewall controls. No API keys are configured for authentication either.\n\nAudit logging is disabled, so there's no record of authentication attempts, authorization failures, or index access patterns. There are also no Index Lifecycle Management policies in place to enforce data retention limits. Looking at the single `app-data` index, it has a routing constraint forcing all shards to the `secondary` zone, which concentrates the data on just two nodes.\n\nThe cluster has five nodes split across two zones: three master-eligible nodes in the primary zone that also handle data, ingest, ML, and transform operations, while two secondary zone nodes only handle data and ingest. The architecture violates best practices by mixing master-eligible responsibilities with data operations, which can cause resource contention and destabilize the cluster. Additionally, there's no field-level or document-level security configured at the index level.\n\nThe cluster is running Elasticsearch 8.11.1, which isn't the latest 8.x release and may be missing security patches. The license is basic tier, which excludes critical security features like audit logging, advanced RBAC, and field/document-level security. The deprecated `kibana` user is still enabled with the `kibana_system` role and should be disabled. TLS private keys are stored in Kubernetes Secrets, which needs further examination for proper secrets management practices.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":671,"cache_read_input_tokens":51317,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":671},"output_tokens":36,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1204d69c-73cb-4b22-b9ff-4b391a67863e","uuid":"72184768-0bd1-464c-ad90-6d34c4e9df14","request_id":"req_011Cc6pzDpDruxG2fK7zoFPN"}
../stage_02/agent.log:1310:../../../../../runs/error-prone-examples/elasticsearch-scale-users-audit-20260616_101353/stages/stage_04/agent.log:196:{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01D9TrFguGTJrRSXcJAe41fi","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01AQaefK68BRaTCN1jinr3YR","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"kubectl -n elasticsearch create configmap config-audit --from-literal=findings.txt=\"$(cat <<'FINDINGS'\n=============================================================\nELASTICSEARCH CLUSTER SECURITY & COMPLIANCE AUDIT\nCluster: es-cluster  |  Version: 8.11.1  |  Date: 2026-06-16\nAuditor: automated read-only audit (no cluster changes made)\n=============================================================\n\nCLUSTER OVERVIEW\n----------------\nNodes    : 5 total (3 master-eligible: es-0/1/2, 2 dedicated data: es-data-0/1)\nStatus   : GREEN, 6 active shards (3 primary + 3 replica)\nLicense  : Basic (free tier)\nAuth     : xpack.security.enabled = true\nTransport: TLS enabled (security4/netty4)\nHTTP     : TLS enabled on port 9200 (plain HTTP rejected)\n\n=============================================================\nFINDINGS BY SEVERITY\n=============================================================\n\n[CRITICAL-1] AUDIT LOGGING DISABLED\nSetting: xpack.security.audit.enabled = false (default, not overridden)\nImpact : No record of authentication events, authorization failures,\n         privilege escalations, or index access. Forensic investigation\n         after a breach is not possible.\nRequired by most compliance frameworks (SOC2, PCI-DSS, HIPAA).\nRemediation: Set xpack.security.audit.enabled=true; requires Gold+ license\n             or Elastic self-managed with audit log output.\n\n[CRITICAL-2] WEAK PASSWORD ON ELASTIC SUPERUSER\nSecret   : elasticsearch/elastic-password\nPassword : elasticpass (dictionary word, 11 chars, no complexity)\nImpact   : The built-in `elastic` superuser account uses a trivially guessable\n           password. Any attacker with network access to port 9200 can\n           authenticate with full cluster control.\nRemediation: Rotate immediately to a random 24+ character credential;\n             store in a secrets manager, not a plain Kubernetes Secret.\n\n[HIGH-1] NO KUBERNETES NETWORKPOLICY IN NAMESPACE\nObserved: kubectl -n elasticsearch get networkpolicy -> \"No resources found\"\nImpact  : Any pod in the Kubernetes cluster can reach es-http:9200 (HTTPS)\n          and all node ports 9300 (transport). There is no network-layer\n          restriction on which workloads are permitted to connect.\nRemediation: Create a NetworkPolicy that allows ingress to port 9200 only\n             from explicitly labelled consumer namespaces/pods; restrict\n             port 9300 (transport) to the elasticsearch namespace only.\n\n[HIGH-2] TLS CERTIFICATE VALIDATION SKIPPED BY INTERNAL CONSUMER\nObserved: curl-test pod uses `curl -sk` (--insecure) to contact Elasticsearch\nImpact  : Connections from curl-test (and likely other consumers following\n          the same pattern) do not verify the server certificate, making\n          them vulnerable to MITM attacks inside the cluster.\nRemediation: Mount the CA certificate (from es-http-tls secret key ca.crt)\n             into consumer pods and use --cacert for all internal connections.\n\n[HIGH-3] SECOND SUPERUSER ACCOUNT IN FILE REALM\nFile realm secret: es-file-realm-aggregate\nUsers (decoded):\n  ops-user    -> superuser role (bcrypt hash)\n  report-user -> read role    (bcrypt hash)\nusers_roles:\n  superuser:ops-user\n  read:report-user\nImpact: ops-user has unrestricted cluster-admin privileges via the file realm,\n        which bypasses native realm password policies. Compromise of the file\n        or the mounted Secret grants full cluster control.\nRemediation: Audit whether ops-user is still required. If operational access\n             is needed, assign a least-privilege role rather than superuser.\n             Rotate file-realm credentials on a defined schedule.\n\n[MEDIUM-1] SELF-SIGNED TLS CERTIFICATES\nCertificates (from /_ssl/certificates):\n  CA  : CN=es-ca (self-signed), expiry 2027-06-16\n  Leaf: CN=es-http, issuer CN=es-ca, expiry 2027-06-16\nImpact: No third-party trust anchor. All consumers must trust the custom CA\n        explicitly; certificate pinning/rotation is entirely self-managed.\n        Expiry is ~1 year from creation — no automated rotation observed.\nRemediation: Integrate with a PKI (e.g. cert-manager with an internal CA\n             or a public CA). Add certificate expiry alerting.\n\n[MEDIUM-2] DEPRECATED kibana USER IS ENABLED\nUser: kibana, roles: [kibana_system]\nMetadata: _deprecated=true, _deprecated_reason=\n  \"Please use the [kibana_system] user instead.\"\nImpact: A deprecated account remains active. If Kibana is connecting with\n        this legacy account, it creates unnecessary credential exposure.\nRemediation: Verify whether any service uses the `kibana` user credential.\n             If not, disable it. Migrate consumers to kibana_system.\n\n[MEDIUM-3] NO ROLE SEPARATION — MASTER NODES ALSO SERVE DATA/INGEST/ML\nNode roles observed:\n  es-0, es-1, es-2 (zone=primary):\n    data, data_cold, data_content, data_frozen, data_hot, data_warm,\n    ingest, master, ml, remote_cluster_client, transform\n  es-data-0, es-data-1 (zone=secondary):\n    data, ingest\nImpact: Data-intensive indexing, ML inference, or transform operations on the\n        primary-zone nodes can starve master-election threads, risking cluster\n        instability. Elasticsearch best practice for production is to dedicate\n        master-eligible nodes (roles: master only).\nRemediation: Set node.roles: [master] on es-0/1/2 and redistribute data/\n             ingest/ML roles to dedicated nodes.\n\n[MEDIUM-4] FIPS MODE NOT ENABLED\nSetting: xpack.security.fips_mode.enabled = false\nImpact: Encryption operations use non-FIPS algorithms (AES/CTR/NoPadding,\n        128-bit key). FIPS 140-2 compliance is not enforced.\nRemediation: If FIPS compliance is required, enable fips_mode and switch to\n             a FIPS-validated JVM and keystore.\n\n[MEDIUM-5] RUN-AS (IMPERSONATION) ENABLED WITH NO EXPLICIT RESTRICTION\nSetting: xpack.security.authc.run_as.enabled = true (default)\nCurrent usage: No users observed with run_as privileges, but the feature is on.\nImpact: If any user is granted run_as privileges (by misconfiguration or\n        future change), they can act as another user without knowing that\n        user's credentials.\nRemediation: If impersonation is not required, set\n             xpack.security.authc.run_as.enabled=false.\n\n[MEDIUM-6] NO HTTP IP FILTER RULES\nSetting: xpack.security.http.filter.allow = []\n         xpack.security.http.filter.deny  = []\n         xpack.security.http.filter.enabled = true (filter mechanism active\n         but no rules defined — effectively allows all IPs)\nImpact: Elasticsearch accepts HTTPS connections from any source IP reachable\n        via Kubernetes networking. Relies entirely on NetworkPolicy (which is\n        absent — see HIGH-1) for layer-3 restriction.\nRemediation: Define xpack.security.http.filter.allow with expected consumer\n             CIDR ranges, or implement NetworkPolicy (preferred).\n\n[LOW-1] KUBERNETES SECRETS ENCRYPTION AT REST NOT CONFIRMED\nSecrets in namespace:\n  elastic-password          (elastic superuser password)\n  es-http-tls               (TLS private key + cert)\n  es-file-realm-aggregate   (file realm credentials)\n  user-provided-file-realm  (file realm source)\nImpact: Without etcd encryption at rest in the Kubernetes cluster, these\n        secrets are stored in plaintext in etcd. Anyone with etcd access\n        can read all credentials and private keys.\nRemediation: Enable Kubernetes EncryptionConfiguration for Secrets in etcd,\n             or use an external secrets manager (Vault, AWS Secrets Manager).\n\n[LOW-2] ELASTICSEARCH VERSION MAY NOT BE LATEST PATCH\nObserved: 8.11.1 (build 2023-11-11)\nImpact: Later 8.x patch releases may include security fixes.\nRemediation: Review Elastic security advisories for 8.11.x and upgrade to\n             the latest 8.x release.\n\n[LOW-3] BASIC LICENSE LIMITS SECURITY FEATURES\nLicense: basic (active)\nImpact: The following security features require Gold or Platinum license and\n        are not available:\n          - Audit logging (xpack.security.audit) — see CRITICAL-1\n          - IP filtering rules (basic only supports HTTP filter config)\n          - Field- and document-level security (DLS/FLS available but\n            limited; xpack.security.dls_fls.enabled=true is set)\n          - FIPS mode (Platinum)\nRemediation: Evaluate upgrade to Gold+ if compliance requirements mandate\n             audit logging or advanced RBAC controls.\n\n=============================================================\nNON-DEFAULT SETTINGS OBSERVED (APPLIED TO LIVE CLUSTER)\n=============================================================\n\nIndex: app-data\n  index.number_of_shards                        : 2  (default=1)\n  index.number_of_replicas                      : 1  (default=1, matches default)\n  index.routing.allocation.require.zone         : secondary\n    -> All primary and replica shards pinned to zone=secondary nodes\n       (es-data-0, es-data-1). Primary-zone nodes (es-0/1/2) hold no shards\n       despite having data roles. This is intentional zone routing.\n       Verify this is documented and intentional; es-data-0/1 become a\n       single point of failure for the app-data index if secondary zone\n       nodes are lost simultaneously.\n  index.routing.allocation.include._tier_preference : data_content\n\nNode attributes (all 5 nodes have zone set):\n  es-0, es-1, es-2   -> zone=primary\n  es-data-0, es-data-1 -> zone=secondary\n\nCluster settings (persistent): {} (all defaults)\nCluster settings (transient) : {} (all defaults)\n\nAuthentication realms (node configuration):\n  file   realm: file1  (order 0) — file-based realm active\n  native realm: native1 (order 1) — native realm active\n  API keys  : enabled (xpack.security.authc.api_key.enabled=true)\n  Bearer token: disabled (xpack.security.authc.token.enabled=false)\n  Enrollment  : disabled (xpack.security.enrollment.enabled=false)\n\nHTTP compression: disabled (http.compression=false)\n\n=============================================================\nINFORMATIONAL OBSERVATIONS\n=============================================================\n\n- network.host=0.0.0.0 on all nodes (listens on all interfaces)\n- Initial master nodes: es-0, es-1, es-2 (election.strategy=supports_voting_only)\n- Discovery seed hosts: es-0/1/2 via es-headless headless service\n- No API keys currently issued (/_security/api_key returns empty)\n- Password hashing algorithm: BCRYPT (file realm), PBKDF2 (API keys) — appropriate\n- No ILM policies observed for app-data index\n- Cluster health: GREEN, no unassigned shards\n\n=============================================================\nAUDIT SCOPE LIMITATIONS\n=============================================================\n\n- Etcd encryption at rest was not inspected (requires cluster-admin access)\n- TLS cipher suites and minimum protocol version could not be extracted\n  from running nodes via the REST API alone\n- Persistent volume encryption (disk at rest) not assessed\n- Kubernetes RBAC for Secret access not audited (requires cluster-admin)\n- No egress network traffic was inspected\n\n=============================================================\nEND OF AUDIT REPORT\n=============================================================\nFINDINGS)\" 2>&1","description":"Create config-audit ConfigMap with findings"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3368,"cache_read_input_tokens":51988,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3368},"output_tokens":34,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1204d69c-73cb-4b22-b9ff-4b391a67863e","uuid":"79f7d3b1-57ca-47cc-84a0-6646bcee0c61","request_id":"req_011Cc6q364yMQgWzJ2X26yZQ"}
