../stage_02/agent.log:1319:../../../../../runs/error-prone-examples/elasticsearch-scale-users-audit-20260616_101353/stages/stage_03/agent.log:132:{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Q1feySL8Ho1npvHYRgwZm4","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clearer picture. The running Elasticsearch cluster from prior stages:\n\n1. StatefulSet `es` (3 pods: es-0, es-1, es-2) - uses `elastic-password` secret for auth, no file-realm\n2. StatefulSet `es-data` (2 pods: es-data-0, es-data-1) - probably data nodes\n\nThe cluster uses:\n- ES 8.11.1\n- `elastic-password` secret for authentication\n- TLS via `es-http-tls` secret\n- No file realm users configured\n\nThe task says \"A newly added reporting user cannot authenticate.\" The oracle checks:\n1. `es-file-realm-aggregate` secret contains both `ops-user` and `report-user` in `users` and `users_roles`\n2. Cluster health is yellow or green\n3. `report-user` can authenticate and read from `app-data` index\n\nSince the ES cluster doesn't have a file realm configured, I need to create the required secrets and add file realm configuration to Elasticsearch so both users can authenticate. First, I'll generate the hashed passwords for both `ops-user` and `report-user`.\n\nI also need to create the `es-file-realm-aggregate` secret with both users merged, then update the Elasticsearch configuration to mount the file-realm files at the correct paths and enable the file realm settings. For Elasticsearch 8.x, the file realm reads from `$ES_PATH_CONF/users` and `$ES_PATH_CONF/users_roles` by default, so I need to ensure those files are properly mounted in the StatefulSet.\n\nModifying the StatefulSet will trigger a rolling restart, but that should be manageable for a 3-node cluster. Let me check what the `file-realm-gen` pod provides and how it generates the bcrypt-hashed passwords using the `elasticsearch-users useradd` tool.\n\nLooking at the actual pod list